# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: oil-gas-scada
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] In petroleum and natural gas extraction, a **Christmas tree**, or **tree**, is an assembly of valves, casing spools, and fittings used to regulate the flow of pipes in an oil well, gas well, water injection well, water disposal well, gas injection well, condensate well, and other types of well.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] The first primitive Christmas tree was used by the Hamill Brothers to bring Spindletop under control.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] It consisted of a T-valve, with a 6-inch (150 mm) and 8-inch (200 mm) valve on the vertical pipe, and a 6-inch valve on the horizontal pipe.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] The vertical valve was closed first, and then the valve to the horizontal pipe.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] Christmas trees are used on both surface and subsea wells.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] It is common to identify the type of tree as either "subsea tree" or "surface tree".
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] Each of these classifications has a number of variations.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] Examples of subsea include conventional, dual bore, mono bore, TFL (through flow line), horizontal, mudline, mudline horizontal, side valve, and TBT (through-bore tree) trees.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] The deepest installed subsea tree is in the Gulf of Mexico at approximately 9,000 feet (2,700 m).
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] Current technical limits are up to around 3000 metres and working temperatures of −50 to 350 °F (−46 to 177 °C) with a pressure of up to 15,000 psi (100 MPa).
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] The primary function of a tree is to control the flow, usually oil or gas, out of the well.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] This leads to a processing facility, storage depot and/or other pipeline eventually leading to a refinery or distribution center (for gas).
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] Flow lines on subsea wells usually lead to a fixed or floating production platform or to a storage ship or barge, known as a floating storage offloading vessel (FSO), or floating processing unit (FPU), or floating production, storage and offloading vessel (FPSO).
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] On producing wells, chemicals or alcohols or oil distillates may be injected to preclude production problems (such as blockages).
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] Functionality may be extended further by using the control system on a subsea tree to monitor, measure, and react to sensor outputs on the tree or even down the well bore.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] The control system attached to the tree controls the downhole safety valve (SCSSV, DHSV, SSSV) while the tree acts as an attachment and conduit means of the control system to the downhole safety valve.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] Tree complexity has increased over the last few decades.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] They are frequently manufactured from blocks of steel containing multiple valves rather than being assembled from individual flanged components.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] This is especially true in subsea applications where the resemblance to Christmas trees no longer exists given the frame and support systems into which the main valve block is integrated.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] Note that a tree and wellhead are separate pieces of equipment not to be mistaken as the same piece.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] The Christmas tree is installed on top of the wellhead.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] A wellhead is used without a Christmas tree during drilling operations, and also for riser tie-back situations that later would have a tree installed at riser top.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] Wells being produced with rod pumps (pump jacks, nodding donkeys, grasshopper pumps, and so on) frequently do not utilize any tree owing the absence of a pressure-containment requirement.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] Subsea and surface trees have a large variety of valve configurations and combinations of manual and/or actuated (hydraulic or pneumatic) valves.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] Examples are identified in API Specifications 6A nd 17D.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] A basic surface tree consists of two or three manual valves (usually gate valves because of their flow characteristics, i.e. low restriction to the flow of fluid when fully open).
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] A typical sophisticated surface tree will have at least four or five valves, normally arranged in a crucifix type pattern (hence the endurance of the term "Christmas tree").
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] The two lower valves are called the master valves (upper and lower respectively).
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] Master valves are normally in the fully open position and are *never* opened or closed when the well is flowing (except in an emergency) to prevent erosion of the valve sealing surfaces.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] The lower master valve will normally be manually operated, while the upper master valve is often hydraulically actuated, allowing it to be used as a means of remotely shutting in the well in the event of emergency.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] An actuated wing valve is normally used to shut in the well when flowing, thus preserving the master valves for positive shut off for maintenance purposes.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] Hydraulic operated wing valves are usually built to be fail safe closed, meaning they require active hydraulic pressure to stay open.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] This feature means that if control fluid fails the well will automatically shut itself in without operator action.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] The right hand valve is often called the flow wing valve or the production wing valve, because it is in the flowpath the hydrocarbons take to production facilities (or the path water or gas will take from production to the well in the case of injection wells).
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] The left hand valve is often called the kill wing valve (KWV).
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] It is primarily used for injection of fluids such as corrosion inhibitors or methanol to prevent hydrate formation.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] In the North Sea, it is called the non-active side arm (NASA).
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] The valve at the top is called the swab valve and lies in the path used for well interventions like wireline and coiled tubing.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] For such operations, a lubricator is rigged up onto the top of the tree and the wire or coil is lowered through the lubricator, past the swab valve and into the well.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] This valve is typically manually operated.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] Some trees have a second swab valve, the two arranged one on top of the other.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] The intention is to allow rigging down equipment from the top of the tree with the well flowing while preserving the two-barrier rule.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] With only a single swab valve, the upper master valve is usually closed to act as the second barrier, forcing the well to be shut in for a day during rig down operations.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] However, avoiding delaying production for a day is usually too small a gain to be worth the extra expense of having a Christmas tree with a second swab valve.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] Subsea trees are available in either vertical or horizontal configurations with further speciality available such as dual bore, monobore, concentric, drill-through, mudline, guidelineless or guideline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] Sub-systems of Subsea trees, might also be further customized to fit individual well needs.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] Subsea trees may range in size and weight from a few tons to approximately 70 tons for high pressure, deepwater (deeper than 3,000 ft or 910 m) guidelineless applications.
[src:oil-gas-scada/christmas-tree-oil-well] Subsea trees contain many additional valves and accessories compared to surface trees.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] A **distributed control system** (**DCS**) is a computerized control system for a process or plant usually with many control loops, in which autonomous controllers are distributed throughout the system, but there is no central operator supervisory control.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] This is in contrast to systems that use centralized controllers; either discrete controllers located at a central control room or within a central computer.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The DCS concept increases reliability and reduces installation costs by localizing control functions near the process plant, with remote monitoring and supervision.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Distributed control systems first emerged in large, high value, safety critical process industries, and were attractive because the DCS manufacturer would supply both the local control level and central supervisory equipment as an integrated package, thus reducing design integration risk.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Today the functionality of Supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) and DCS systems are very similar, but DCS tends to be used on large continuous process plants where high reliability and security is important, and the control room is not necessarily geographically remote.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Many machine control systems exhibit similar properties as plant and process control systems do.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The key attribute of a DCS is its reliability due to the distribution of the control processing around nodes in the system.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] This mitigates a single processor failure.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] If a processor fails, it will only affect one section of the plant process, as opposed to a failure of a central computer which would affect the whole process.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] This distribution of computing power local to the field Input/Output (I/O) connection racks also ensures fast controller processing times by removing possible network and central processing delays.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The accompanying diagram is a general model which shows functional manufacturing levels using computerised control.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Levels 1 and 2 are the functional levels of a traditional DCS, in which all equipment are part of an integrated system from a single manufacturer.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Levels 3 and 4 are not strictly process control in the traditional sense, but where production control and scheduling takes place.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The processor nodes and operator graphical displays are connected over proprietary or industry standard networks, and network reliability is increased by dual redundancy cabling over diverse routes.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] This distributed topology also reduces the amount of field cabling by siting the I/O modules and their associated processors close to the process plant.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The processors receive information from input modules, process the information and decide control actions to be signalled by the output modules.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The field inputs and outputs can be analog signals e.g.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] 4–20 mA DC current loop or two-state signals that switch either "on" or "off", such as relay contacts or a semiconductor switch.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] DCSs are connected to sensors and actuators and use setpoint control to control the flow of material through the plant.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] A typical application is a PID controller fed by a flow meter and using a control valve as the final control element.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The DCS sends the setpoint required by the process to the controller which instructs a valve to operate so that the process reaches and stays at the desired setpoint.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Large oil refineries and chemical plants have several thousand I/O points and employ very large DCS.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Processes are not limited to fluidic flow through pipes, however, and can also include things like paper machines and their associated quality controls, variable speed drives and motor control centers, cement kilns, mining operations, ore processing facilities, and many others.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] DCSs in very high reliability applications can have dual redundant processors with "hot" switch over on fault, to enhance the reliability of the control system.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Although 4–20 mA has been the main field signalling standard, modern DCS systems can also support fieldbus digital protocols, such as Foundation Fieldbus, profibus, HART, modbus, PC Link, etc.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Modern DCSs also support neural networks and fuzzy logic applications.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Recent research focuses on the synthesis of optimal distributed controllers, which optimizes a certain H-infinity or the H 2 control criterion.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Distributed control systems (DCS) are dedicated systems used in manufacturing processes that are continuous or batch-oriented.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Process control of large industrial plants has evolved through many stages.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Initially, control would be from panels local to the process plant.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] However this required a large amount of human oversight to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently-staffed central control room.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Effectively this was the centralisation of all the localised panels, with the advantages of lower manning levels and easier overview of the process.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Often the controllers were behind the control room panels, and all automatic and manual control outputs were transmitted back to plant.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] However, whilst providing a central control focus, this arrangement was inflexible as each control loop had its own controller hardware, and continual operator movement within the control room was required to view different parts of the process.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] With the coming of electronic processors and graphic displays it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] These could be distributed around plant, and communicate with the graphic display in the control room or rooms.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The distributed control system was born.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The introduction of DCSs allowed easy interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Early minicomputers were used in the control of industrial processes since the beginning of the 1960s.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The IBM 1800, for example, was an early computer that had input/output hardware to gather process signals in a plant for conversion from field contact levels (for digital points) and analog signals to the digital domain.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The first industrial control computer system was built 1959 at the Texaco Port Arthur, Texas, refinery with an RW-300 of the Ramo-Wooldridge Company.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] In 1975, both HONEYWELL and Japanese electrical engineering firm Yokogawa introduced their own independently produced DCS's - TDC 2000 and CENTUM systems, respectively.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] US-based Bristol also introduced their UCS 3000 universal controller in 1975.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] In 1978 Valmet introduced their own DCS system called Damatic (latest web-based generation Valmet DNAe).
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] In 1980, Bailey (now part of ABB) introduced the NETWORK 90 system, Fisher Controls (now part of Emerson Electric) introduced the PROVoX system, Fischer & Porter Company (now also part of ABB) introduced DCI-4000 (DCI stands for Distributed Control Instrumentation).
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The DCS largely came about due to the increased availability of microcomputers and the proliferation of microprocessors in the world of process control.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Computers had already been applied to process automation for some time in the form of both direct digital control (DDC) and setpoint control.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] In the early 1970s Taylor Instrument Company, (now part of ABB) developed the 1010 system, Foxboro the FOX1 system, Fisher Controls the DC2 system and Bailey Controls the 1055 systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] All of these were DDC applications implemented within minicomputers (DEC PDP-11, Varian Data Machines, MODCOMP etc.) and connected to proprietary Input/Output hardware.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Sophisticated (for the time) continuous as well as batch control was implemented in this way.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] A more conservative approach was setpoint control, where process computers supervised clusters of analog process controllers.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] A workstation provided visibility into the process using text and crude character graphics.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Availability of a fully functional graphical user interface was a way away.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Central to the DCS model was the inclusion of control function blocks.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Function blocks evolved from early, more primitive DDC concepts of "Table Driven" software.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] One of the first embodiments of object-oriented software, function blocks were self-contained "blocks" of code that emulated analog hardware control components and performed tasks that were essential to process control, such as execution of PID algorithms.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Function blocks continue to endure as the predominant method of control for DCS suppliers, and are supported by key technologies such as Foundation Fieldbus today.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Midac Systems, of Sydney, Australia, developed an objected-oriented distributed direct digital control system in 1982.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The central system ran 11 microprocessors sharing tasks and common memory and connected to a serial communication network of distributed controllers each running two Z80s.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The system was installed at the University of Melbourne.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Digital communication between distributed controllers, workstations and other computing elements (peer to peer access) was one of the primary advantages of the DCS.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Attention was duly focused on the networks, which provided the all-important lines of communication that, for process applications, had to incorporate specific functions such as determinism and redundancy.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] As a result, many suppliers embraced the IEEE 802.4 networking standard.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] This decision set the stage for the wave of migrations necessary when information technology moved into process automation and IEEE 802.3 rather than IEEE 802.4 prevailed as the control LAN.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] In the 1980s, users began to look at DCSs as more than just basic process control.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] A very early example of a Direct Digital Control DCS was completed by the Australian business Midac in 1981–82 using R-Tec Australian designed hardware.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The system installed at the University of Melbourne used a serial communications network, connecting campus buildings back to a control room "front end".
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Each remote unit ran two Z80 microprocessors, while the front end ran eleven Z80s in a parallel processing configuration with paged common memory to share tasks and that could run up to 20,000 concurrent control objects.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] It was believed that if openness could be achieved and greater amounts of data could be shared throughout the enterprise that even greater things could be achieved.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The first attempts to increase the openness of DCSs resulted in the adoption of the predominant operating system of the day: *UNIX*.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] UNIX and its companion networking technology TCP-IP were developed by the US Department of Defense for openness, which was precisely the issue the process industries were looking to resolve.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] As a result, suppliers also began to adopt Ethernet-based networks with their own proprietary protocol layers.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The full TCP/IP standard was not implemented, but the use of Ethernet made it possible to implement the first instances of object management and global data access technology.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The 1980s also witnessed the first PLCs integrated into the DCS infrastructure.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Plant-wide historians also emerged to capitalize on the extended reach of automation systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The first DCS supplier to adopt UNIX and Ethernet networking technologies was Foxboro, who introduced the I/A Series system in 1987.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The drive toward openness in the 1980s gained momentum through the 1990s with the increased adoption of commercial off-the-shelf (COTS) components and IT standards.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Probably the biggest transition undertaken during this time was the move from the UNIX operating system to the Windows environment.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] While the realm of the real time operating system (RTOS) for control applications remains dominated by real time commercial variants of UNIX or proprietary operating systems, everything above real-time control has made the transition to Windows.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The introduction of Microsoft at the desktop and server layers resulted in the development of technologies such as OLE for process control (OPC), which is now a de facto industry connectivity standard.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Internet technology also began to make its mark in automation and the world, with most DCS HMI supporting Internet connectivity.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The 1990s were also known for the "Fieldbus Wars", where rival organizations competed to define what would become the IEC fieldbus standard for digital communication with field instrumentation instead of 4–20 milliamp analog communications.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The first fieldbus installations occurred in the 1990s.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Towards the end of the decade, the technology began to develop significant momentum, with the market consolidated around Ethernet I/P, Foundation Fieldbus and Profibus PA for process automation applications.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Fieldbus technics have been used to integrate machine, drives, quality and condition monitoring applications to one DCS with Valmet DNA system.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The impact of COTS, however, was most pronounced at the hardware layer.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] For years, the primary business of DCS suppliers had been the supply of large amounts of hardware, particularly I/O and controllers.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The initial proliferation of DCSs required the installation of prodigious amounts of this hardware, most of it manufactured from the bottom up by DCS suppliers.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Standard computer components from manufacturers such as Intel and Motorola, however, made it cost prohibitive for DCS suppliers to continue making their own components, workstations, and networking hardware.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] As the suppliers made the transition to COTS components, they also discovered that the hardware market was shrinking fast.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] COTS not only resulted in lower manufacturing costs for the supplier, but also steadily decreasing prices for the end users, who were also becoming increasingly vocal over what they perceived to be unduly high hardware costs.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The traditional DCS suppliers introduced new generation DCS System based on the latest Communication and IEC Standards, which resulting in a trend of combining the traditional concepts/functionalities for PLC and DCS into a one for all solution—named "Process Automation System" (PAS).
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The gaps among the various systems remain at the areas such as: the database integrity, pre-engineering functionality, system maturity, communication transparency and reliability.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] While it is expected the cost ratio is relatively the same (the more powerful the systems are, the more expensive they will be), the reality of the automation business is often operating strategically case by case.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The current next evolution step is called Collaborative Process Automation Systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] To compound the issue, suppliers were also realizing that the hardware market was becoming saturated.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The life cycle of hardware components such as I/O and wiring is also typically in the range of 15 to over 20 years, making for a challenging replacement market.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Many of the older systems that were installed in the 1970s and 1980s are still in use today, and there is a considerable installed base of systems in the market that are approaching the end of their useful life.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Developed industrial economies in North America, Europe, and Japan already had many thousands of DCSs installed, and with few if any new plants being built, the market for new hardware was shifting rapidly to smaller, albeit faster growing regions such as China, Latin America, and Eastern Europe.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Because of the shrinking hardware business, suppliers began to make the challenging transition from a hardware-based business model to one based on software and value-added services.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] It is a transition that is still being made today.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The applications portfolio offered by suppliers expanded considerably in the '90s to include areas such as production management, model-based control, real-time optimization, plant asset management (PAM), Real-time performance management (RPM) tools, alarm management, and many others.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] To obtain the true value from these applications, however, often requires a considerable service content, which the suppliers also provide.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Increasingly, and ironically, DCS are becoming centralised at plant level, with the ability to log into the remote equipment.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] This enables operator to control both at enterprise level ( macro ) and at the equipment level (micro), both within and outside the plant, because the importance of the physical location drops due to interconnectivity primarily thanks to wireless and remote access.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] The more wireless protocols are developed and refined, the more they are included in DCS.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] DCS controllers are now often equipped with embedded servers and provide on-the-go web access.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Whether DCS will lead Industrial Internet of Things (IIOT) or borrow key elements from remains to be seen.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] Many vendors provide the option of a mobile HMI, ready for both Android and iOS.
[src:oil-gas-scada/distributed-control-system] With these interfaces, the threat of security breaches and possible damage to plant and process are now very real.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The **petroleum industry**, also known as the **oil industry**, includes the global processes of exploration, extraction, refining, transportation (often by oil tankers and pipelines), and marketing of petroleum products.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The largest volume products of the industry are fuel oil and gasoline (petrol).
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Petroleum is also the raw material for many chemical products, including pharmaceuticals, solvents, fertilizers, pesticides, synthetic fragrances, and plastics.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The industry is usually divided into three major components: upstream, midstream, and downstream.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Upstream regards exploration and extraction of crude oil, midstream encompasses transportation and storage of it, and downstream concerns refining crude oil into various end products.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Petroleum is vital to many industries, and is necessary for the maintenance of industrial civilization in its current configuration, making it a critical concern for many nations.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Oil accounts for a large percentage of the world's energy consumption, ranging from a low of 32% for Europe and Asia, to a high of 53% for the Middle East.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Other geographic regions' consumption patterns are as follows: South and Central America (44%), Africa (41%), and North America (40%).
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The world consumes 36 billion barrels (5.8 km3) of oil per year, with developed nations being the largest consumers.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The United States consumed 18% of the oil produced in 2015.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The production, distribution, refining, and retailing of petroleum taken as a whole represents the world's largest industry in terms of dollar value.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Petroleum is a naturally occurring liquid found in rock formations.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] It consists of a complex mixture of hydrocarbons of various molecular weights, plus other organic compounds.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] It is generally accepted that oil is formed mostly from the carbon rich remains of ancient plankton after exposure to heat and pressure in Earth's crust over hundreds of millions of years.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Over time, the decayed residue was covered by layers of mud and silt, sinking further down into Earth's crust and preserved there between hot and pressured layers, gradually transforming into oil reservoirs.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Petroleum in an unrefined state has been utilized by humans for over 5000 years.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Oil in general has been used since early human history to keep fires ablaze and in warfare.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Its importance to the world economy however, evolved slowly, with whale oil being used for lighting in the 19th century and wood and coal used for heating and cooking well into the 20th century.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Even though the Industrial Revolution generated an increasing need for energy, this was initially met mainly by coal, and from other sources including whale oil.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] However, when it was discovered that kerosene could be extracted from crude oil and used as a lighting and heating fuel, the demand for petroleum increased greatly, and by the early twentieth century had become the most valuable commodity traded on world markets.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Imperial Russia produced 3,500 tons of oil in 1825 and doubled its output by mid-century.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The first drilled oil wells in Baku were built in 1871–1872 by Ivan Mirzoev, an Armenian businessman who is referred to as one of the 'founding fathers' of Baku's oil industry.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] At the turn of the 20th century, Imperial Russia's output of oil, almost entirely from the Apsheron Peninsula, accounted for half of the world's production and dominated international markets.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Nearly 200 small refineries operated in the suburbs of Baku by 1884.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] As a side effect of these early developments, the Apsheron Peninsula emerged as the world's "oldest legacy of oil pollution and environmental negligence".
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] In 1846 Baku (Bibi-Heybat settlement) featured the first ever well drilled with percussion tools to a depth of 21 meters for oil exploration.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] In 1878 Ludvig Nobel and his Branobel company "revolutionized oil transport" by commissioning the first oil tanker and launching it on the Caspian Sea.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Samuel Kier established America's first oil refinery in Pittsburgh on Seventh avenue near Grant Street in 1853.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Ignacy Łukasiewicz built one of the first modern oil-refineries near Jasło (then in the Austrian dependent Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria in Central European Galicia), present-day Poland, in 1854–56.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Galician refineries were initially small, as demand for refined fuel was limited.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The refined products were used in artificial asphalt, machine oil and lubricants, in addition to Łukasiewicz's kerosene lamp.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] As kerosene lamps gained popularity, the refining industry grew in the area.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The first commercial oil-well in Canada became operational in 1858 at Oil Springs, Ontario (then Canada West).
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Businessman James Miller Williams dug several wells between 1855 and 1858 before discovering a rich reserve of oil four metres below ground.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Williams extracted 1.5 million litres of crude oil by 1860, refining much of it into kerosene-lamp oil.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Some historians challenge Canada's claim to North America's first oil field, arguing that Pennsylvania's famous Drake Well was the continent's first.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] But there is evidence to support Williams, not least of which is that the Drake well did not come into production until August 28, 1859.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The controversial point might be that Williams found oil above bedrock while Edwin Drake's well located oil within a bedrock reservoir.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The discovery at Oil Springs touched off an oil boom which brought hundreds of speculators and workers to the area.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Canada's first gusher (flowing well) erupted on January 16, 1862, when local oil-man John Shaw struck oil at 158 feet (48 m).
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] For a week the oil gushed unchecked at levels reported as high as 3,000 barrels per day.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The first modern oil-drilling in the United States began in West Virginia and Pennsylvania in the 1850s.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Edwin Drake's 1859 well near Titusville, Pennsylvania, typically considered the first true modern oil well, touched off a major boom.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] In the first quarter of the 20th century, the United States overtook Russia as the world's largest oil producer.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] By the 1920s, oil fields had been established in many countries including Canada, Poland, Sweden, Ukraine, the United States, Peru and Venezuela.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The first successful oil tanker, the *Zoroaster*, was built in 1878 in Sweden, designed by Ludvig Nobel.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] A number of new tanker designs developed in the 1880s.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] In the early 1930s the Texas Company developed the first mobile steel barges for drilling in the brackish coastal areas of the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] In 1937 Pure Oil Company (now part of Chevron Corporation) and its partner Superior Oil Company (now part of ExxonMobil Corporation) used a fixed platform to develop a field in 14 feet (4.3 m) of water, one mile (1.6 km) offshore of Calcasieu Parish, Louisiana.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] In early 1947 Superior Oil erected a drilling/production oil-platform in 20 ft (6.1 m) of water some 18 miles off Vermilion Parish, Louisiana.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Kerr-McGee Oil Industries, as operator for partners Phillips Petroleum (ConocoPhillips) and Stanolind Oil & Gas (BP), completed its historic Ship Shoal Block 32 well in November 1947, months before Superior actually drilled a discovery from their Vermilion platform farther offshore.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] In any case, that made Kerr-McGee's Gulf of Mexico well, Kermac No.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] 16, the first oil discovery drilled out of sight of land.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Forty-four Gulf of Mexico exploratory wells discovered 11 oil and natural gas fields by the end of 1949.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] During World War II (1939–1945) control of oil supply from Romania, Baku, the Middle East and the Dutch East Indies played a huge role in the events of the war and the ultimate victory of the Allies.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The Anglo-Soviet invasion of Iran (1941) secured Allied control of oil-production in the Middle East.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The expansion of Imperial Japan to the south aimed largely at accessing the oil-fields of the Dutch East Indies.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Germany, cut off from sea-borne oil supplies by Allied blockade, failed in Operation Edelweiss to secure the Caucasus oil-fields for the Axis military in 1942, while Romania deprived the Wehrmacht of access to Ploesti oilfields – the largest in Europe – from August 1944.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Cutting off the East Indies oil-supply (especially via submarine campaigns) considerably weakened Japan in the latter part of the war.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] After World War II ended in 1945, the countries of the Middle East took the lead in oil production from the United States.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Important developments since World War II include deep-water drilling, the introduction of the drillship, and the growth of a global shipping network for petroleum – relying upon oil tankers and pipelines.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] In 1949 the first offshore oil-drilling at Oil Rocks (Neft Dashlari) in the Caspian Sea off Azerbaijan eventually resulted in a city built on pylons.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] In the 1960s and 1970s, multi-governmental organizations of oil–producing nations – OPEC and OAPEC – played a major role in setting petroleum prices and policy.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Oil spills and their cleanup have become an issue of increasing political, environmental, and economic importance.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] New fields of hydrocarbon production developed in places such as Siberia, Sakhalin, Venezuela and North and West Africa.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] With the advent of hydraulic fracturing and other horizontal drilling techniques, shale play has seen an enormous uptick in production.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Areas of shale such as the Permian Basin and Eagle-Ford have become huge hotbeds of production for the largest oil corporations in the United States.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The following table shows the ten largest national oil companies ranked by reserves and by production in 2012.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Most upstream work in the oil field or on an oil well is contracted out to drilling contractors and oil field service companies.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Aside from the NOCs which dominate the Upstream sector, there are many international companies that have a market share.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Midstream operations are sometimes classified within the downstream sector, but these operations compose a separate and discrete sector of the petroleum industry.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] While some upstream companies carry out certain midstream operations, the midstream sector is dominated by a number of companies that specialize in these services.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The oil and gas industry spends only 0.4% of its net sales on research & development (R&D) which is in comparison with a range of other industries the lowest share.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Governments such as the United States government provide a heavy public subsidy to petroleum companies, with major tax breaks at various stages of oil exploration and extraction, including the costs of oil field leases and drilling equipment.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] In recent years, enhanced oil recovery techniques – most notably multi-stage drilling and hydraulic fracturing ("fracking") – have moved to the forefront of the industry as this new technology plays a crucial and controversial role in new methods of oil extraction.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Researchers have studied whether donations from oil and gas companies want to make lawmakers vote on environmental issues.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Reports that oil and gas contributions to U.S. congressional candidates rose from about $35 million in 2010 to over $84 million in 2018.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] He also notes that this increase occurred as independent outside spending also grew through groups like independent committees, which are also called super PACs .
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Oil and gas companies are said to support candidates whose voting records align with the industry's policy preferences, especially on environmental regulation.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Civil rights groups such as the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People have supported environmental and climate justice and have opposed policies that increase reliance on fossil fuels.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] There is criticism that comes towards the oil and gas drilling in how they affect the community overall which can take a toll on the ecosystem.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] They often call for less fossil fuel development and more use of energy development like wind and solar power.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Some petroleum industry operations have been responsible for water pollution through by-products of refining and oil spills.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Though hydraulic fracturing has significantly increased natural gas extraction, there is some belief and evidence to support that consumable water has seen increased in methane contamination due to this gas extraction.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Leaks from underground tanks and abandoned refineries may also contaminate groundwater in surrounding areas.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Hydrocarbons that comprise refined petroleum are resistant to biodegradation and have been found to remain present in contaminated soils for years.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] To hasten this process, bioremediation of petroleum hydrocarbon pollutants is often employed by means of aerobic degradation.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] More recently, other bioremediative methods have been explored such as phytoremediation and thermal remediation.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The industry is the largest industrial source of emissions of volatile organic compounds (VOCs), a group of chemicals that contribute to the formation of ground-level ozone (smog).
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The combustion of fossil fuels produces greenhouse gases and other air pollutants as by-products.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Pollutants include nitrogen oxides, sulphur dioxide, volatile organic compounds and heavy metals.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Researchers have discovered that the petrochemical industry can produce ground-level ozone pollution at higher amounts in winter than in summer.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Greenhouse gases emissions from oil extraction and refining vary significantly across deposits due to differences in extraction techniques (such as flaring, methane venting, and fugitive emissions) as well as oil- and reservoir-specific characteristics.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Greenhouse gases caused by producing, refining, and burning fossil fuels drive climate change.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] In 1959, at a symposium organised by the American Petroleum Institute for the centennial of the American oil industry, the physicist Edward Teller warned of the danger of global climate change.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] Edward Teller explained that carbon dioxide "in the atmosphere causes a greenhouse effect" and that burning more fossil fuels could "melt the icecaps and submerge New York".
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, founded by the United Nations in 1988, concludes that human-sourced greenhouse gases are responsible for most of the observed temperature increase since the middle of the twentieth century.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] As a result of climate change concerns, many people have begun using other methods of energy such as solar and wind.
[src:oil-gas-scada/petroleum-industry] This recent shift has some petroleum enthusiasts skeptical about the future of the industry.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] A **pipeline** is a system of pipes for long-distance transportation of a liquid or gas, typically to a market area for consumption.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Industry datasets indicate the length of the global trunk/transmission pipeline network is on the order of ~2.19 million km by 2025, with North America accounting for ~44%.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The United States had 65%, Russia had 8%, and Canada had 3%, thus 76% of all pipeline were in these three countries.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The main attribute to pollution from pipelines is caused by corrosion and leakage.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pipelines are useful for transporting water for drinking or irrigation over long distances when it needs to move over hills, or where canals or channels are poor choices due to considerations of evaporation, pollution, or environmental impact.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Oil pipelines are made from steel or plastic tubes which are usually buried.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The oil is moved through the pipelines by pump stations along the pipeline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Natural gas (and similar gaseous fuels) are pressurized into liquids known as natural gas liquids (NGLs).
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Natural gas pipelines are constructed of carbon steel.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Hydrogen pipeline transport is the transportation of hydrogen through a pipe.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pipelines are one of the safest ways of transporting materials as compared to road or rail.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Hence in war, pipelines are often the target of military attacks.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The first crude oil pipeline was built by the Oil Transport Association, which constructed a 2-inch (51 mm) wrought iron pipeline over a 6-mile (9.7 km) track from an oil field in Pennsylvania to a railroad station in Oil Creek, in the 1860s.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Some of the first major submarine pipelines were constructed across the English Channel in 1944 during Operation Pluto.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] These provided an estimated 8 per cent of all petroleum products used by the Allies on the Western Front between the Normandy landings and the end of Second World War.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pipelines are generally the most economical way to transport large quantities of oil, refined oil products or natural gas over land.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] For example, in 2014, pipeline transport of crude oil cost about $5 per barrel, while rail transport cost about $10 to $15 per barrel.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Trucking has even higher costs due to the additional labor required; employment on completed pipelines represents only "1% of that of the trucking industry.".
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] In the United States, 70% of crude oil and petroleum products are shipped by pipeline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] (23% are by ship, 4% by truck, and 3% by rail) In Canada for natural gas and petroleum products, 97% are shipped by pipeline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Natural gas (and similar gaseous fuels) are lightly pressurized into liquids known as Natural Gas Liquids (NGLs).
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Small NGL processing facilities can be located in oil fields so the butane and propane liquid under light pressure of 125 pounds per square inch (860 kilopascals), can be shipped by rail, truck or pipeline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Propane can be used as a fuel in oil fields to heat various facilities used by the oil drillers or equipment and trucks used in the oil patch.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] EG: Propane will convert from a gas to a liquid under light pressure, 100 psi, give or take depending on temperature, and is pumped into cars and trucks at less than 125 psi (860 kPa) at retail stations.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pipelines and rail cars use about double that pressure to pump at 250 psi (1,700 kPa).
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The distance to ship propane to markets is much shorter, as thousands of natural-gas processing plants are located in or near oil fields.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Many Bakken Basin oil companies in North Dakota, Montana, Manitoba and Saskatchewan gas fields separate the NGLs in the field, allowing the drillers to sell propane directly to small wholesalers, eliminating the large refinery control of product and prices for propane or butane.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The most recent major pipeline to start operating in North America is a TransCanada natural gas line going north across the Niagara region bridges.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] This gas line carries Marcellus shale gas from Pennsylvania and other tied in methane or natural gas sources into the Canadian province of Ontario.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] It began operations in the fall of 2012, supplying 16 percent of all the natural gas used in Ontario.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] This new US-supplied natural gas displaces the natural gas formerly shipped to Ontario from western Canada in Alberta and Manitoba, thus dropping the government regulated pipeline shipping charges because of the significantly shorter distance from gas source to consumer.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] To avoid delays and US government regulation, many small, medium and large oil producers in North Dakota have decided to run an oil pipeline north to Canada to meet up with a Canadian oil pipeline shipping oil from west to east.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] This allows the Bakken Basin and Three Forks oil producers to get higher negotiated prices for their oil because they will not be restricted to just one wholesale market in the US.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The distance from the biggest oil patch in North Dakota, in Williston, North Dakota, is only about 85 miles or 137 kilometres to the Canada–US border and Manitoba.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Mutual funds and joint ventures are the largest investors in new oil and gas pipelines.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] In the fall of 2012, the US began exporting propane to Europe, known as LPG, as wholesale prices there are much higher than in North America.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Additionally, a pipeline is currently being constructed from North Dakota to Illinois, commonly known as the Dakota Access Pipeline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] As more North American pipelines are built, even more exports of LNG, propane, butane, and other natural gas products occur on all three US coasts.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] To give insight, North Dakota Bakken region's oil production has grown by 600% from 2007 to 2015.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] However, pipelines provide a cheaper means to transport by volume.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Enbridge in Canada is applying to reverse an oil pipeline going from east to west (Line 9) and expanding it and using it to ship western Canadian bitumen oil eastward.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] From a presently rated 250,000 barrels equivalent per day pipeline, it will be expanded to between 1.0 and 1.3 million barrels per day.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] It will bring western oil to refineries in Ontario, Michigan, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Quebec and New York by early 2014.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] New Brunswick will also refine some of this western Canadian crude and export some crude and refined oil to Europe from its deep water oil ULCC loading port.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Although pipelines can be built under the sea, that process is economically and technically demanding, so the majority of oil at sea is transported by tanker ships.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Similarly, it is often more economically feasible to transport natural gas in the form of LNG; however, the break-even point between LNG and pipelines would depend on the volume of natural gas and the distance it travels.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The market size for oil and gas pipeline construction experienced tremendous growth prior to the economic downturn in 2008.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] After faltering in 2009, demand for pipeline expansion and updating increased the following year as energy production grew.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] By 2012, almost 32,000 miles (51,000 km) of North American pipeline were being planned or under construction.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] When pipelines are constrained, additional pipeline product transportation options may include the use of drag reducing agents, or by transporting product via truck or rail.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Oil pipelines are made from steel or plastic tubes with inner diameter typically from 4 to 48 inches (100 to 1,220 mm).
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Most pipelines are typically buried at a depth of about 3 to 6 feet (0.91 to 1.83 m).
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] To protect pipes from impact, abrasion, and corrosion, a variety of methods are used.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] These can include wood lagging (wood slats), concrete coating, rockshield, high-density polyethylene, imported sand padding, sacrificial cathodes and padding machines.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Crude oil contains varying amounts of paraffin wax and in colder climates wax buildup may occur within a pipeline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Often these pipelines are inspected and cleaned using pigging, the practice of using devices known as "pigs" to perform various maintenance operations on a pipeline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The devices are also known as "scrapers" or "Go-devils".
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] "Smart pigs" (also known as "intelligent" or "intelligence" pigs) are used to detect anomalies in the pipe such as dents, metal loss caused by corrosion, cracking or other mechanical damage.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] These devices are launched from pig-launcher stations and travel through the pipeline to be received at any other station down-stream, either cleaning wax deposits and material that may have accumulated inside the line or inspecting and recording the condition of the line.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] For natural gas, pipelines are constructed of carbon steel and vary in size from 2 to 60 inches (51 to 1,524 mm) in diameter, depending on the type of pipeline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The gas is pressurized by compressor stations and is odorless unless mixed with a mercaptan odorant where required by a regulating authority.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Until damaged during the Russian invasion of Ukraine, the Russian–Ukrainian *Transammiak* line was the longest ammonia pipeline in the world, at 2,500 km.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] It connected the TogliattiAzot facility in Russia to the exporting Black Sea-port of Odesa in Ukraine.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pipelines have been used for transportation of ethanol in Brazil, and there are several ethanol pipeline projects in Brazil and the United States.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The main problems related to the transport of ethanol by pipeline are its corrosive nature and tendency to absorb water and impurities in pipelines, which are not problems with oil and natural gas.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Insufficient volumes and cost-effectiveness are other considerations limiting construction of ethanol pipelines.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] In the US minimal amounts of ethanol are transported by pipeline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Most ethanol is shipped by rail, the main alternatives being truck and barge.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Delivering ethanol by pipeline is the most desirable option, but ethanol's affinity for water and solvent properties require the use of a dedicated pipeline, or significant cleanup of existing pipelines.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Slurry pipelines are sometimes used to transport coal or ore from mines.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The material to be transported is closely mixed with water before being introduced to the pipeline; at the far end, the material must be dried.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] One example is a 525-kilometre (326 mi) slurry pipeline which is planned to transport iron ore from the Minas-Rio mine (producing 26.5 million tonnes per year) to the Port of Açu in Brazil.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] An existing example is the 85-kilometre (53 mi) Savage River Slurry pipeline in Tasmania, Australia, possibly the world's first when it was built in 1967.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] It includes a 366-metre (1,201 ft) bridge span at 167 metres (548 ft) above the Savage River.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Hydrogen pipeline transport is a transportation of hydrogen through a pipe as part of the hydrogen infrastructure.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Hydrogen pipeline transport is used to connect the point of hydrogen production or delivery of hydrogen with the point of demand.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Most hydrogen is produced at the place of demand with every 50 to 100 miles (80 to 161 km) an industrial production facility.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The 1938 Rhine-Ruhr 240-kilometre (150 mi) hydrogen pipeline is still in operation.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] As of 2004, there are 900 miles (1,400 km) of low-pressure hydrogen pipelines in the US and 930 miles (1,500 km) in Europe.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] In steel pipelines, gaseous hydrogen can accelerate fatigue-crack growth and reduce the apparent fracture toughness of line-pipe and welds, so materials must be qualified for hydrogen service using fracture-mechanics criteria.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] ASME B31.12 for hydrogen piping and pipelines provides such a qualification route (e.g., threshold stress-intensity in hydrogen and optional fatigue-crack-growth data).
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Recent evaluations on API 5L X70 line-pipe show measurable toughness reductions and faster crack growth under blended-hydrogen conditions, while recent reviews summarize hydrogen uptake, trapping and mitigation specific to pipeline steels.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Two millennia ago, the ancient Romans made use of large aqueducts to transport water from higher elevations by building the aqueducts in graduated segments that allowed gravity to push the water along until it reached its destination.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Hundreds of these were built throughout Europe and elsewhere, and along with flour mills were considered the lifeline of the Roman Empire.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The ancient Chinese also made use of channels and pipe systems for public works.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The famous Han dynasty court eunuch Zhang Rang (d.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] 189 AD) once ordered the engineer Bi Lan to construct a series of square-pallet chain pumps outside the capital city of Luoyang.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] These chain pumps serviced the imperial palaces and living quarters of the capital city as the water lifted by the chain pumps was brought in by a stoneware pipe system.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The 530 km (330 mi) Goldfields Water Supply Scheme in Western Australia using 750 mm (30 in) pipe and completed in 1903 was the largest water supply scheme of its time.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Examples of significant water pipelines in South Australia are the Morgan-Whyalla pipeline (completed 1944) and Mannum-Adelaide pipeline (completed 1955) pipelines, both part of the larger Snowy Mountains scheme.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Two Los Angeles, California aqueducts, the Owens Valley aqueduct (completed 1913) and the Second Los Angeles Aqueduct (completed 1970), include extensive use of pipelines.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The Great Manmade River of Libya supplies 3.68 million m3 (4.81 million yd3) of water each day to Tripoli, Benghazi, Sirte, and several other cities in Libya.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The pipeline is over 2,800 kilometres (1,700 mi) long, and is connected to wells tapping an aquifer over 500 metres (1,600 ft) underground.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] District heating or *teleheating* systems consist of a network of insulated feed and return pipes which transport heated water, pressurized hot water, or sometimes steam to the customer.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] While steam is hottest and may be used in industrial processes due to its higher temperature, it is less efficient to produce and transport due to greater heat losses.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Heat transfer oils are generally not used for economic and ecological reasons.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The typical annual loss of thermal energy through distribution is around 10%, as seen in Norway's district heating network.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] District heating pipelines are normally installed underground, with some exceptions.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Within the system, heat storage may be installed to even out peak load demands.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Heat is transferred into the central heating of the dwellings through heat exchangers at heat substations, without mixing of the fluids in either system.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Bars in the Veltins-Arena, a major football ground in Gelsenkirchen, Germany, are interconnected by a 5-kilometre-long (3.1 mi) beer pipeline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] In Randers city in Denmark, the so-called Thor Beer pipeline was operated.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Originally, copper pipes ran directly from the brewery, but when the brewery moved out of the city in the 1990s, Thor Beer replaced it with a giant tank.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] A three-kilometre beer pipeline was completed in Bruges, Belgium in September 2016 to reduce truck traffic on the city streets.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The village of Hallstatt in Austria, which is known for its long history of salt mining, claims to contain "the oldest industrial pipeline in the world", dating back to 1595.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] It was constructed from 13,000 hollowed-out tree trunks to transport brine 40 kilometres (25 mi) from Hallstatt to Ebensee.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Between 1978 and 1994, a 15 km milk pipeline ran between the Dutch island of Ameland and Holwerd on the mainland, of which 8 km was beneath the Wadden Sea.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Every day, 30,000 litres of milk produced on the island were transported to be processed on the mainland.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Rather than transporting fluids, pneumatic tubes are usually used to transport solids in a cylindrical container by compressed air or by partial vacuum.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] They were most popular in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, and were used to transport small solid objects within a building, e.g. documents in an office or money in a bank.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] By the 21st century, pneumatic tube transport had been mostly superseded by digital solutions for transporting information, but is still used in cases where convenience and speed in a local environment are important.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Hospitals, for example, use them to deliver drugs and specimens.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] In places, a pipeline may have to cross water expanses, such as small seas, straits and rivers.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] In many instances, they lie entirely on the seabed.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] These pipelines are referred to as "marine" pipelines (also, "submarine" or "offshore" pipelines).
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] They are used primarily to carry oil or gas, but transportation of water is also important.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] In offshore projects, a distinction is made between a "flowline" and a pipeline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The former is an *intrafield* pipeline, in the sense that it is used to connect subsea wellheads, manifolds and the platform *within* a particular development field.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The latter, sometimes referred to as an "export pipeline", is used to bring the resource to shore.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The construction and maintenance of marine pipelines imply logistical challenges that are different from those onland, mainly because of wave and current dynamics, along with other geohazards.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Group of smaller interconnected pipelines forming complex networks with the purpose of bringing crude oil or natural gas from several nearby wells to a treatment plant or processing facility.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] In this group, pipelines are usually short—a couple hundred metres—and with small diameters.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Sub-sea pipelines for collecting product from deep water production platforms are also considered gathering systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Mainly long pipes with large diameters, moving products (oil, gas, refined products) between cities, countries and even continents.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] These transportation networks include several compressor stations in gas lines or pump stations for crude and multi-products pipelines.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Composed of several interconnected pipelines with small diameters, used to take the products to the final consumer.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Feeder lines to distribute gas to homes and businesses downstream.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pipelines at terminals for distributing products to tanks and storage facilities are included in this groups.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] When a pipeline is built, the construction project not only covers the civil engineering work to lay the pipeline and build the pump/compressor stations, it also has to cover all the work related to the installation of the field devices that will support remote operation.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The pipeline is routed along what is known as a "right of way".
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pipeline design: The pipeline project may take a number of forms, including the construction of a new pipeline, conversion of existing pipeline from one fuel type to another, or improvements to facilities on a current pipeline route.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Obtaining approval: Once the design is finalized and the first pipeline customers have purchased their share of capacity, the project must be approved by the relevant regulatory agencies.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Testing: Once construction is completed, the new pipeline is subjected to tests to ensure its structural integrity.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] These may include hydrostatic testing and line packing.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Russia has "Pipeline Troops" as part of the Rear Services, who are trained to build and repair pipelines.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Russia is the only country to have Pipeline Troops.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The US government, mainly through the EPA, the FERC and others, reviews proposed pipeline projects in order to comply with the Clean Water Act, the National Environmental Policy Act, other laws and, in some cases, municipal laws.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The Biden administration has sought to permit the respective states and tribal groups to appraise and potentially block the proposed projects.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Field devices are instrumentation, data gathering units and communication systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The field instrumentation includes flow, pressure, and temperature gauges/transmitters, and other devices to measure the relevant data required.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] These instruments are installed along the pipeline on some specific locations, such as injection or delivery stations, pump stations (liquid pipelines) or compressor stations (gas pipelines), and block valve stations.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The information measured by these field instruments is then gathered in local remote terminal units (RTU) that transfer the field data to a central location in real time using communication systems, such as satellite channels, microwave links, or cellular phone connections.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pipelines are controlled and operated remotely, from what is usually known as the "Main Control Room".
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] In this center, all the data related to field measurement is consolidated in one central database.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The data is received from multiple RTUs along the pipeline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] It is common to find RTUs installed at every station along the pipeline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The SCADA system at the Main Control Room receives all the field data and presents it to the pipeline operator through a set of screens or Human Machine Interface, showing the operational conditions of the pipeline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The operator can monitor the hydraulic conditions of the line, as well as send operational commands (open/close valves, turn on/off compressors or pumps, change setpoints, etc.) through the SCADA system to the field.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pipeline networks are composed of several pieces of equipment that operate together to move products from location to location.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Known also as "supply" or "inlet" station, is the beginning of the system, where the product is injected into the line.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Storage facilities, pumps or compressors are usually located at these locations.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] for gas pipelines, are located along the line to move the product through the pipeline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The location of these stations is defined by the topography of the terrain, the type of product being transported, or operational conditions of the network.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Known also as "intermediate stations", these facilities allow the pipeline operator to deliver part of the product being transported.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] These are the first line of protection for pipelines.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] With these valves the operator can isolate any segment of the line for maintenance work or isolate a rupture or leak.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Even though it is not a design rule, it is a very usual practice in liquid pipelines.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The location of these stations depends exclusively on the nature of the product being transported, the trajectory of the pipeline and/or the operational conditions of the line.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] This is a special type of valve station, where the operator can release some of the pressure from the line.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Regulators are usually located at the downhill side of a peak.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Known also as "outlet" stations or terminals, this is where the product will be distributed to the consumer.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] It could be a tank terminal for liquid pipelines or a connection to a distribution network for gas pipelines.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Since oil and gas pipelines are an important asset of the economic development of almost any country, it has been required either by government regulations or internal policies to ensure the safety of the assets, and the population and environment where these pipelines run.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pipeline companies face government regulation, environmental constraints and social situations.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Government regulations may define minimum staff to run the operation, operator training requirements, pipeline facilities, technology and applications required to ensure operational safety.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] For example, in the State of Washington it is mandatory for pipeline operators to be able to detect and locate leaks of 8 percent of maximum flow within fifteen minutes or less.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Social factors also affect the operation of pipelines.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Product theft is sometimes also a problem for pipeline companies.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] In this case, the detection levels should be under two percent of maximum flow, with a high expectation for location accuracy.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Various technologies and strategies have been implemented for monitoring pipelines, from physically walking the lines to satellite surveillance.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The most common technology to protect pipelines from occasional leaks is Computational Pipeline Monitoring or CPM.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] CPM takes information from the field related to pressures, flows, and temperatures to estimate the hydraulic behavior of the product being transported.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Once the estimation is completed, the results are compared to other field references to detect the presence of an anomaly or unexpected situation, which may be related to a leak.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The American Petroleum Institute has published several articles related to the performance of CPM in liquids pipelines.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Where a pipeline containing passes under a road or railway, it is usually enclosed in a protective casing.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] This casing is vented to the atmosphere to prevent the build-up of flammable gases or corrosive substances, and to allow the air inside the casing to be sampled to detect leaks.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The *casing vent*, a pipe protruding from the ground, often doubles as a warning marker called a *casing vent marker*.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pipelines are generally laid underground because temperature is less variable.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Because pipelines are usually metal, this helps to reduce the expansion and shrinkage that can occur with weather changes.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] However, in some cases it is necessary to cross a valley or a river on a pipeline bridge.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pipelines for centralized heating systems are often laid on the ground or overhead.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pipelines for petroleum running through permafrost areas as Trans-Alaska Pipeline are often run overhead in order to avoid melting the frozen ground by hot petroleum which would result in sinking the pipeline in the ground.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Maintenance of pipelines includes checking cathodic protection levels for the proper range, surveillance for construction, erosion, or leaks by foot, land vehicle, boat, or air, and running cleaning pigs when there is anything carried in the pipeline that is corrosive.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] US pipeline maintenance rules are covered in Code of Federal Regulations (CFR) sections, 49 CFR 192 for natural gas pipelines, and 49 CFR 195 for petroleum liquid pipelines.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] In the US, onshore and offshore pipelines used to transport oil and gas are regulated by the Pipeline and Hazardous Materials Safety Administration (PHMSA).
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Certain offshore pipelines used to produce oil and gas are regulated by the Minerals Management Service (MMS).
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] In Canada, pipelines are regulated by either the provincial regulators or, if they cross provincial boundaries or the Canada–US border, by the National Energy Board (NEB).
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Government regulations in Canada and the United States require that buried fuel pipelines must be protected from corrosion.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Often, the most economical method of corrosion control is by use of pipeline coating in conjunction with cathodic protection and technology to monitor the pipeline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Above ground, cathodic protection is not an option.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The coating is the only external protection.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pipelines for major energy resources (petroleum and natural gas) are not merely an element of trade.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] They connect to issues of geopolitics and international security as well, and the construction, placement, and control of oil and gas pipelines often figure prominently in state interests and actions.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] A notable example of pipeline politics occurred at the beginning of the year 2009, wherein a dispute between Russia and Ukraine ostensibly over pricing led to a major political crisis.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Russian state-owned gas company Gazprom cut off natural gas supplies to Ukraine after talks between it and the Ukrainian government fell through.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] In addition to cutting off supplies to Ukraine, Russian gas flowing through Ukraine—which included nearly all supplies to Southeastern Europe and some supplies to Central and Western Europe—was cut off, creating a major crisis in several countries heavily dependent on Russian gas as fuel.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Russia was accused of using the dispute as leverage in its attempt to keep other powers, and particularly the European Union, from interfering in its "near abroad".
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Because the solvent fraction of dilbit typically comprises volatile aromatics such as naptha and benzene, reasonably rapid carrier vaporization can be expected to follow an above-ground spill—ostensibly enabling timely intervention by leaving only a viscous residue that is slow to migrate.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Effective protocols to minimize exposure to petrochemical vapours are well-established, and oil spilled from the pipeline would be unlikely to reach the aquifer unless incomplete remediation were followed by the introduction of another carrier (e.g. a series of torrential downpours).
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The introduction of benzene and other volatile organic compounds (collectively BTEX) to the subterranean environment compounds the threat posed by a pipeline leak.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Particularly if followed by rain, a pipeline breach would result in BTEX dissolution and equilibration of benzene in water, followed by percolation of the admixture into the aquifer.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Benzene can cause many health problems and is carcinogenic with EPA Maximum Contaminant Level (MCL) set at 5 μg/L for potable water.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Although it is not well studied, single benzene exposure events have been linked to acute carcinogenesis.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Additionally, the exposure of livestock, mainly cattle, to benzene has been shown to cause many health issues, such as neurotoxicity, fetal damage and fatal poisoning.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The entire surface of an above-ground pipeline can be directly examined for material breach.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pooled petroleum is unambiguous, readily spotted, and indicates the location of required repairs.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Because the effectiveness of remote inspection is limited by the cost of monitoring equipment, gaps between sensors, and data that requires interpretation, small leaks in buried pipe can sometimes go undetected.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pipeline developers do not always prioritize effective surveillance against leaks.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] They are insulated from extremes in ambient temperature, they are shielded from ultraviolet rays, and they are less exposed to photodegradation.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Buried pipes are isolated from airborne debris, electrical storms, tornadoes, hurricanes, hail, and acid rain.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] They are protected from nesting birds, rutting mammals, and stray buckshot.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Buried pipe is less vulnerable to accident damage (e.g. automobile collisions) and less accessible to vandals, saboteurs, and terrorists.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Previous work has shown that a 'worst-case exposure scenario' can be limited to a specific set of conditions.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Based on the advanced detection methods and pipeline shut-off SOP developed by TransCanada, the risk of a substantive or large release over a short period of time contaminating groundwater with benzene is unlikely.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Detection, shutoff, and remediation procedures would limit the dissolution and transport of benzene.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Therefore, the exposure of benzene would be limited to leaks that are below the limit of detection and go unnoticed for extended periods of time.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Leak detection is monitored through a SCADA system that assesses pressure and volume flow every 5 seconds.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] A pinhole leak that releases small quantities that cannot be detected by the SCADA system (<1.5% flow) could accumulate into a substantive spill.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Detection of pinhole leaks would come from a visual or olfactory inspection, aerial surveying, or mass-balance inconsistencies.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] It is assumed that pinhole leaks are discovered within the 14-day inspection interval; however, snow cover and location (e.g. remote, deep) could delay detection.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Benzene typically makes up 0.1 to 1.0% of oil and will have varying degrees of volatility and dissolution based on environmental factors.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Even with pipeline leak volumes within SCADA detection limits, sometimes pipeline leaks are misinterpreted by pipeline operators to be pump malfunctions, or other problems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The Enbridge Line 6B crude oil pipeline failure in Marshall, Michigan, on July 25, 2010, was thought by operators in Edmonton to be from column separation of the dilbit in that pipeline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The leak in wetlands along the Kalamazoo River was only confirmed 17 hours after it happened by a local gas company employee.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Although the Pipeline and Hazardous Materials Safety Administration (PHMSA) has standard baseline incident frequencies to estimate the number of spills, TransCanada altered these assumptions based on improved pipeline design, operation, and safety.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Whether these adjustments are justified is debatable as these assumptions resulted in a nearly ten-fold decrease in spill estimates.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Given that the pipeline crosses 247 miles of the Ogallala Aquifer, or 14.5% of the entire pipeline length, and the 50-year life of the entire pipeline is expected to have between 11 and 91 spills, approximately 1.6 to 13.2 spills can be expected to occur over the aquifer.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] An estimate of 13.2 spills over the aquifer, each lasting 14 days, results in 184 days of potential exposure over the 50-year lifetime of the pipeline.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] In the reduced-scope worst-case exposure scenario, the volume of a pinhole leak at 1.5% of max flow-rate for 14 days has been estimated at 189,000 barrels or 7.9 million gallons of oil.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] According to PHMSA's incident database, only 0.5% of all spills in the last ten years were more than 10,000 barrels.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Benzene is considered a light aromatic hydrocarbon with high solubility and high volatility.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] It is unclear how temperature and depth would impact the volatility of benzene, so assumptions have been made that benzene in oil (1% weight by volume) would not volatilize before equilibrating with water.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Using the octanol-water partition coefficient and a 100-year precipitation event for the area, a worst-case estimate of 75 mg/L of benzene is anticipated to flow toward the aquifer.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The actual movement of the plume through groundwater systems is not well described, although one estimate is that up to 4.9 billion gallons of water in the Ogallala Aquifer could become contaminated with benzene at concentrations above the MCL.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The Final Environmental Impact Statement from the State Department does not include a quantitative analysis because it assumed that most benzene will volatilize.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] One of the major concerns over dilbit is the difficulty in cleaning it up.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] When the aforementioned Enbridge Line 6B crude oil pipeline ruptured in Marshall, Michigan in 2010, at least 843,000 gallons of dilbit were spilled.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] After detection of the leak, booms and vacuum trucks were deployed.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Heavy rains caused the river to overtop existing dams, and carried dilbit 30 miles downstream before the spill was contained.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Remediation work collected over 1.1 million gallons of oil and almost 200,000 cubic yards of oil-contaminated sediment and debris from the Kalamazoo River system.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] However, oil was still being found in affected waters in October 2012.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pipelines can help ensure a country's economic well-being and as such present a likely target of terrorists or wartime adversaries.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Fossil fuels can be transported by pipeline, rail, truck or ship, though natural gas requires compression or liquefaction to make vehicle transport economical.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] For transport of crude oil via these four modes, various reports rank pipelines as proportionately causing less human death and property damage than rail and truck and spilling less oil than truck.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pipelines conveying flammable or explosive material, such as natural gas or oil, pose special safety concerns.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] While corrosion, pressure, and equipment failure are common causes, excavation damage is also a leading accident type that can be avoided by calling 811 before digging near pipelines.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] Pipelines can be the target of vandalism, sabotage, or even terrorist attacks.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] For example, between early 2011 and July 2012, a natural gas pipeline connecting Egypt to Israel and Jordan was attacked 15 times.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] In 2019, a fuel pipeline north of Mexico City exploded after fuel thieves tapped into the line.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] At least sixty-six people were reported to have been killed.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] In war, pipelines are often the target of military attacks, as destruction of pipelines can seriously disrupt enemy logistics.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] On 26 September 2022, a series of explosions and subsequent major gas leaks occurred on the Nord Stream 1 and Nord Stream 2 pipelines that run to Europe from Russia under the Baltic Sea.
[src:oil-gas-scada/pipeline-transport] The leaks are believed to have been caused by an act of sabotage.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs can range from small modular devices with tens of inputs and outputs (I/O), in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] They can be designed for many arrangements of digital and analog I/O, extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs were first developed in the automobile manufacturing industry to provide flexible, rugged and easily programmable controllers to replace hard-wired relay logic systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Dick Morley, who invented the first PLC, the Modicon 084, for General Motors in 1968, is considered the father of PLC.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] A PLC is an example of a hard real-time system since output results must be produced in response to input conditions within a limited time, otherwise unintended operation may result.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The PLC originated in the late 1960s in the automotive industry in the US and was designed to replace relay logic systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Before, control logic for manufacturing was mainly composed of relays, cam timers, drum sequencers, and dedicated closed-loop controllers.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The hard-wired nature of these components made it difficult for design engineers to alter the automation process.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Changes would require rewiring and careful updating of the documentation.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] When general-purpose computers became available, they were soon applied to control logic in industrial processes.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] These early computers were unreliable and required specialist programmers and strict control of working conditions, such as temperature, cleanliness, and power quality.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The PLC provided several advantages over earlier automation systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] It was designed to tolerate the industrial environment better than systems intended for office use, and was more reliable, compact, and required less maintenance than relay systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] It was easily expandable with additional I/O modules.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] While relay systems required tedious and sometimes complicated hardware changes in case of reconfiguration, a PLC can be reconfigured by loading new or modified code.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] This allowed for easier iteration over manufacturing process design.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] With a simple programming language focused on logic and switching operations, it was more user-friendly than computers using general-purpose programming languages.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Early PLCs were programmed in ladder logic, which strongly resembled a schematic diagram of relay logic.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] It also permitted its operation to be monitored.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In recent years, the introduction of virtual PLCs has expanded the scope of programmable logic controllers.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Virtual PLCs are software-based controllers that simulate the functions of traditional PLCs but are executed on general-purpose hardware, offering a more cost-effective and flexible alternative.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] These controllers enable automation systems to be managed without the need for dedicated hardware, making them ideal for applications requiring simulation, remote control, or cloud-based systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In 1968, GM Hydramatic, the automatic transmission division of General Motors, issued a request for proposals for an electronic replacement for hard-wired relay systems based on a white paper written by engineer Edward R.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The winning proposal came from Bedford Associates from Bedford, Massachusetts.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The result, built in 1969, was the first PLC and designated the *084*, because it was Bedford Associates' eighty-fourth project.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Bedford Associates started a company, **Modicon, Inc.**, dedicated to developing, manufacturing, selling, and servicing this new product, which they named **Modicon** (standing for "modular digital controller").
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] One of the people who worked on that project was Dick Morley, who is considered to be the father of the PLC.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The Modicon brand was sold in 1977 to Gould Electronics and later to Schneider Electric, its current owner.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] About this same time, Modicon created Modbus, a data communications protocol to be used with its PLCs.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Modbus has since become a standard open protocol commonly used to connect many industrial electrical devices.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] One of the first Modicon 084 models built is now on display at Schneider Electric's facility in North Andover, Massachusetts.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] It was presented to Modicon by GM, when the unit was retired after nearly twenty years of uninterrupted service.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Modicon used the 84 moniker at the end of its product range like Modicon Micro 84 and Modicon TSX CSY 84 until after the 984 made its appearance.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In a parallel development, Odo Josef Struger is sometimes known as the "father of the programmable logic controller" as well.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] He was involved in the invention of the Allen-Bradley programmable logic controller.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Prior to the release of the IBM "Personal Computer" in 1981, these devices were commonly known simply as "Programmable Controllers", or "PC's.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] But rapid expansion of the personal computer industry in the early 1980's, the abbreviation "PC" was rapidly and universally accepted as a reference to "Personal Computers".
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Odo was later credited with coining the "PLC" acronym to distinguish these two technologies, And the inclusion of the word "Logic" was an easy choice as "Ladder Logic" had already been accepted as the name of the programming language.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Allen-Bradley (now a brand owned by Rockwell Automation) went on to become the dominant PLC manufacturer in the United States during his tenure.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Struger played a leadership role in developing IEC 61131-3 PLC programming language standards.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Allen-Bradley's PLC-5 family, preceded by the 1774-PLC (released in the 1980's, was the first modular design found in modern-day systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] While Modicon was the most popular of the first full featured PLC's through the early 1980's, Allen Bradley overtook them in the mid-1980's and grew to own the largest market share of PLC hardware and software in North America.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Many early PLC programming applications were not capable of graphical representation of the logic, and so it was instead represented as a series of logic expressions in some kind of Boolean format, similar to Boolean algebra.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] As programming terminals evolved, because ladder logic was a familiar format used for electro-mechanical control panels, it became more commonly used.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Newer formats, such as state logic, function block diagrams, and structured text exist.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Ladder logic remains popular because PLCs solve the logic in a predictable and repeating sequence, and ladder logic allows the person writing the logic to see any issues with the timing of the logic sequence more easily than would be possible in other formats.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Up to the mid-1990s, PLCs were programmed using proprietary programming panels or special-purpose programming terminals, which often had dedicated function keys representing the various logical elements of PLC programs.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Some proprietary programming terminals displayed the elements of PLC programs as graphic symbols, but plain ASCII character representations of contacts, coils, and wires were common.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Programs were stored on cassette tape cartridges.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Facilities for printing and documentation were minimal due to a lack of memory capacity.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The oldest PLCs used magnetic-core memory.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] A PLC is an industrial microprocessor-based controller with programmable memory used to store program instructions and various functions.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs require a programming device that is used to develop and later download the created program into the memory of the controller.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Modern PLCs generally contain a real-time operating system, such as OS-9 or VxWorks.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] There are two types of mechanical design for PLC systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] A *single box* (also called a *brick*) is a small programmable controller that fits all units and interfaces into one compact casing, although, typically, additional expansion modules for inputs and outputs are available.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The second design type – a *modular* PLC – has a chassis (also called a *rack*) that provides space for modules with different functions, such as power supply, processor, selection of I/O modules and communication interfaces – which all can be customized for the particular application.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Several racks can be administered by a single processor and may have thousands of inputs and outputs.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Either a special high-speed serial I/O link or comparable communication method is used so that racks can be distributed away from the processor, reducing the wiring costs for large plants.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Discrete (digital) signals can only take *on* or *off* value (1 or 0, *true* or *false*).
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Examples of devices providing a discrete signal include limit switches and photoelectric sensors.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Analog signals can use voltage or current that is analogous to the monitored variable and can take any value within their scale.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Pressure, temperature, flow, and weight are often represented by analog signals.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] These are typically interpreted as integer values with various ranges of accuracy depending on the device and the number of bits available to store the data.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] For example, an analog 0 to 10 V or 4-20 mA current loop input would be converted into an integer value of 0 to 32,767.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The PLC will take this value and translate it into the desired units of the process so the operator or program can read it.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Some special processes need to work permanently with minimum unwanted downtime.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Therefore, it is necessary to design a system that is fault tolerant.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In such cases, to increase the system availability in the event of hardware component failure, redundant CPU or I/O modules with the same functionality can be added to a hardware configuration to prevent a total or partial process shutdown due to hardware failure.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Other redundancy scenarios could be related to safety-critical processes, for example, large hydraulic presses could require that two PLCs turn on an output before the press can come down in case one PLC does not behave properly.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Programmable logic controllers are intended to be used by engineers without a programming background.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] For this reason, a graphical programming language called ladder logic was first developed.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] It resembles the schematic diagram of a system built with electromechanical relays and was adopted by many manufacturers and later standardized in the IEC 61131-3 control systems programming standard.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] As of 2015, it is still widely used, thanks to its simplicity.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] As of 2015, the majority of PLC systems adhere to the IEC 61131-3 standard that defines two textual programming languages: Structured Text (similar to Pascal) and Instruction List; as well as three graphical languages: ladder logic, function block diagram and sequential function chart.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Instruction List was deprecated in the third edition of the standard.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Modern PLCs can be programmed in a variety of ways, from the relay-derived ladder logic to programming languages such as specially adapted dialects of BASIC and C.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] While the fundamental concepts of PLC programming are common to all manufacturers, differences in I/O addressing, memory organization, and instruction sets mean that PLC programs are never perfectly interchangeable between different makers.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Even within the same product line of a single manufacturer, different models may not be directly compatible.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Manufacturers develop programming software for their PLCs.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In addition to being able to program PLCs in multiple languages, they provide common features like hardware diagnostics and maintenance, software debugging, and offline simulation.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLC programs are typically written in a programming device, which can take the form of a desktop console, special software on a personal computer, or a handheld device.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The program is then downloaded to the PLC through a cable connection or over a network.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] It is stored either in non-volatile flash memory or battery-backed-up RAM on the PLC.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In some PLCs, the program is transferred from the programming device using a programming board that writes the program into a removable chip, such as EPROM, that is then inserted into the PLC.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] An incorrectly programmed PLC can result in lost productivity and dangerous conditions for programmed equipment.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLC simulation is a feature often found in PLC programming software.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] It allows for testing and debugging early in a project's development.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Testing the project in simulation improves its quality, increases the level of safety associated with equipment and can save time during the installation and commissioning of automated control applications since many scenarios can be tried and tested before the system is activated.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The main difference compared to most other computing devices is that PLCs are intended for and therefore tolerant of more severe environmental conditions (such as dust, moisture, heat, cold), while offering extensive input/output (I/O) to connect the PLC to sensors and actuators.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLC input can include simple digital elements such as limit switches, analog variables from process sensors (such as temperature and pressure), and more complex data such as that from positioning or machine vision systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLC output can include elements such as indicator lamps, sirens, electric motors, pneumatic or hydraulic cylinders, magnetic relays, solenoids, or analog outputs.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The input/output arrangements may be built into a simple PLC, or the PLC may have external I/O modules attached to a fieldbus or computer network that plugs into the PLC.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The functionality of the PLC has evolved over the years to include sequential relay control, motion control, process control, distributed control systems, and networking.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The data handling, storage, processing power, and communication capabilities of some modern PLCs are approximately equivalent to desktop computers.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLC-like programming combined with remote I/O hardware allows a general-purpose desktop computer to serve as a PLC in certain applications.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The most basic function of a programmable logic controller is to emulate the functions of electromechanical relays.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Within the PLC programming environment, discrete inputs are given a unique address, and a PLC instruction can test if the input state is on or off.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Just as a series of relay contacts performs a logical AND function, not allowing current to pass unless all the contacts are closed, so a series of *examine if on* instructions will energize its output storage bit if all the input bits are on.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Similarly, a parallel set of instructions will perform a logical OR.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In an electromechanical relay wiring diagram, a group of contacts controlling one coil is called a *rung* of a *ladder diagram*, and this concept is also used to describe PLC logic.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The output of each rung sets or clears a storage bit, which may be associated with a discrete output or which may be an *internal coil* with no physical connection.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Such internal coils can be used, for example, as a common element in multiple separate rungs.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] More advanced instructions of the PLC may be implemented as functional blocks, which carry out some operation, such as manipulating an internal variable, when enabled by a logical input and which produce outputs to signal, for example, completion or errors.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs use built-in ports, such as USB, Ethernet, RS-232, RS-485, or RS-422 to communicate with external devices (sensors, actuators) and systems (programming tools, SCADA and other user interfaces).
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Communication is carried over various industrial network protocols, like Modbus, or EtherNet/IP.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Many of these protocols are vendor specific.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Formerly, some manufacturers offered dedicated communication modules as an add-on function where the processor had no network connection built in.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs used in larger I/O systems may have peer-to-peer (P2P) communication between processors.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] This allows separate parts of a complex process to have individual control while allowing the subsystems to coordinate over the communication link.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs may need to interact with people for the purpose of configuration, alarm reporting, or everyday control.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] A human-machine interface (HMI) is employed for this purpose.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] HMIs are also referred to as man-machine interfaces (MMIs) and graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] A simple system may use buttons and lights to interact with the user.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Text displays are available as well as graphical touch screens.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] More complex systems use programming and monitoring software installed on a computer, with the PLC connected via a communication interface.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] A PLC works in a program scan cycle, where it executes its program repeatedly.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The program follows the sequence of instructions.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] It typically takes a time span of tens of milliseconds for the processor to evaluate all the instructions and update the status of all outputs.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] If the system contains remote I/O—for example, an external rack with I/O modules—then that introduces additional uncertainty in the response time of the PLC system.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Special-purpose I/O modules may be used where the scan time of the PLC is too long to allow predictable performance.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Precision timing modules, or counter modules for use with shaft encoders, are used where the scan time would be too long to reliably count pulses or detect the sense of rotation of an encoder.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] This allows even a relatively slow PLC to still interpret the counted values to control a machine, as the accumulation of pulses is done by a dedicated module that is unaffected by the speed of program execution.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] As PLCs became more advanced, methods were developed to change the sequence of ladder execution, and subroutines were implemented.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Prior to the discovery of the Stuxnet computer worm in June 2010, the security of PLCs received little attention.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Modern programmable controllers generally contain real-time operating systems, which can be vulnerable to exploits in a similar way as desktop operating systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs can also be attacked by gaining control of a computer they communicate with.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Since 2011, these concerns have grown as networking is becoming more commonplace in the PLC environment, connecting the previously separated plant floor networks and office networks.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In February 2021, Rockwell Automation publicly disclosed a critical vulnerability affecting its Logix controller family.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The secret cryptographic key used to verify communication between the PLC and workstation could be extracted from the programming software (Studio 5000 Logix Designer) and used to remotely change program code and configuration of a connected controller.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The vulnerability was given a severity score of 10 out of 10 on the Common Vulnerability Scoring System.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Safety PLCs can be either a standalone device or safety-rated hardware and functionality added to existing controller architectures (Allen-Bradley GuardLogix, Siemens F-series, etc.).
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] These differ from conventional PLC types by being suitable for safety-critical applications for which PLCs have traditionally been supplemented with hard-wired safety relays and areas of the memory dedicated to the safety instructions.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The standard of safety level is the safety integrity level (SIL).
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] A safety PLC might be used to control access to a robot cell with trapped-key access, or to manage the shutdown response to an emergency stop button on a conveyor production line.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Such PLCs typically have a restricted regular instruction set augmented with safety-specific instructions designed to interface with emergency stop buttons, light screens, and other safety-related devices.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs are well adapted to a range of automation tasks.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] These are typically industrial processes in manufacturing where the cost of developing and maintaining the automation system is high relative to the total cost of the automation system, and where changes to the system would be expected during its operational life.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs contain input and output devices compatible with industrial devices and controls; little electrical design is required, and the design problem centers on expressing the desired sequence of operations.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] PLC applications are typically highly customized systems, so the cost of a packaged PLC is low compared to the cost of a specific custom-built controller design.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] On the other hand, in the case of mass-produced goods, customized control systems are economical.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] This is due to the lower cost of the components, which can be optimally chosen instead of a *generic* solution, and where the non-recurring engineering charges are spread over thousands or millions of units.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] These are for small machines and systems with low or medium volume.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] They can execute PLC languages such as ladder logic, function block diagram and sequential function chart.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] They are similar to traditional PLCs, but their small size allows developers to design them into custom printed circuit boards like a microcontroller, without computer programming knowledge, but with a language that is easy to use, modify and maintain.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Architecturally, they sit between the classic PLC or micro-PLC and microcontrollers.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Automotive applications are an example; millions of units are built each year, and very few end-users alter the programming of these controllers.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] However, some specialty vehicles, such as transit buses, economically use PLCs instead of custom-designed controllers, because the volumes are low and the development cost would be uneconomical.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Very complex process control, such as that used in the chemical industry, may require algorithms and performance beyond the capability of even high-performance PLCs.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Very high-speed or precision controls may also require customized solutions; for example, aircraft flight controls.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Single-board computers using semi-customized or fully proprietary hardware may be chosen for very demanding control applications where the high development and maintenance cost can be supported.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] **Soft PLCs** running on desktop-type computers can interface with industrial I/O hardware while executing programs within a version of commercial operating systems adapted for process control needs.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] The rising popularity of single-board computers has also had an influence on the development of PLCs.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Traditional PLCs are generally closed platforms, but some newer PLCs (e.g., groov EPIC from Opto 22, ctrlX from Bosch Rexroth, PFC200 from Wago, PLCnext from Phoenix Contact, and Revolution Pi from Kunbus) provide the features of traditional PLCs on an open platform.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In more recent years, small products called programmable logic relays (PLRs) or smart relays have become more common and accepted.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] These are similar to PLCs and are used in light industries where only a few points of I/O are needed, and low cost is desired.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] These small devices are typically made in a common physical size and shape by several manufacturers and branded by the makers of larger PLCs to fill their low-end product range.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Most of these have 8 to 12 discrete inputs, 4 to 8 discrete outputs, and up to 2 analog inputs.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Most have an RS-232 or RS-485 port for connecting to a PC so that programmers can use user-friendly software for programming instead of the small LCD and push-button set for this purpose.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Unlike regular PLCs that are usually modular and greatly expandable, the PLRs are usually not modular or expandable, but their cost can be significantly lower than that a PLC, and they still offer robust design and deterministic execution of the logic.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] A variant of PLCs, used in remote locations, is the remote terminal unit or RTU.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] An RTU is typically a low power, ruggedized PLC whose key function is to manage the communications links between the site and the central control system (typically SCADA) or in some modern systems, "The Cloud".
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] Unlike factory automation using wired communication protocols such as Ethernet, communications links to remote sites are often radio-based and are less reliable.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] To account for the reduced reliability, RTU will buffer messages or switch to alternate communications paths.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] When buffering messages, the RTU will timestamp each message so that a full history of site events can be reconstructed.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] RTUs, being PLCs, have a wide range of I/O and are fully programmable, typically with languages from the IEC 61131-3 standard that is common to many PLCs, RTUs and DCSs.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] In remote locations, it is common to use an RTU as a gateway for a PLC, where the PLC is performing all site control and the RTU is managing communications, time-stamping events and monitoring ancillary equipment.
[src:oil-gas-scada/programmable-logic-controller] On sites with only a handful of I/O, the RTU may also be the site PLC and will perform both communications and control functions.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The operator interfaces, which enable monitoring and the issuing of process commands, such as controller setpoint changes, are handled through the SCADA computer system.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The subordinated operations, e.g. the real-time control logic or controller calculations, are performed by networked modules connected to the field sensors and actuators.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The SCADA concept was developed to be a universal means of remote-access to a variety of local control modules, which could be from different manufacturers and allowing access through standard automation protocols.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] In practice, large SCADA systems have grown to become similar to DCSs in function, while using multiple means of interfacing with the plant.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] They can control large-scale processes spanning multiple sites, and work over large distances.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] It is one of the most commonly used types of industrial control systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The key attribute of a SCADA system is its ability to perform a supervisory operation over a variety of other proprietary devices.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Level 1 contains the programmable logic controllers (PLCs) or remote terminal units (RTUs).
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Level 2 contains the SCADA to readings and equipment status reports that are communicated to level 2 SCADA as required.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Data is then compiled and formatted in such a way that a control room operator using the human-machine interface (HMI) can make supervisory decisions to adjust or override normal RTU (PLC) controls.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Data may also be fed to a historian, often built on a commodity database management system, to allow trending and other analytical auditing.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] SCADA systems typically use a *tag database*, which contains data elements called *tags* or *points*, which relate to specific instrumentation or actuators within the process system.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Data is accumulated against these unique process control equipment tag references.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] This is the core of the SCADA system, gathering data on the process and sending control commands to the field connected devices.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] It refers to the computer and software responsible for communicating with the field connection controllers, which are RTUs and PLCs, and includes the HMI software running on operator workstations.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] In smaller SCADA systems, the supervisory computer may be composed of a single PC, in which case the HMI is a part of this computer.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] In larger SCADA systems, the master station may include several HMIs hosted on client computers, multiple servers for data acquisition, distributed software applications, and disaster recovery sites.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] formation providing continuous control and monitoring in the event of a server malfunction or breakdown.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] connect to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory computer system.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] system, using radio, GSM or satellite for communications, and being ruggedised to survive from -20C to +70C or even -40C to +85C without external heating or cooling equipment.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] PLCs are connected to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory system.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] In factory automation, PLCs typically have a high speed connection to the SCADA system.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] In remote applications, such as a large water treatment plant, PLCs may connect directly to SCADA over a wireless link, or more commonly, utilise an RTU for the communications management.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] For economical reasons, PLCs are often used for remote sites where there is a large I/O count, rather than utilising an RTU alone.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] This connects the supervisory computer system to the RTUs and PLCs, and may use industry standard or manufacturer proprietary protocols.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Both RTUs and PLCs operate autonomously on the near-real time control of the process, using the last command given from the supervisory system.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Failure of the communications network does not necessarily stop the plant process controls, and on resumption of communications, the operator can continue with monitoring and control.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Some critical systems will have dual redundant data highways, often cabled via diverse routes.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The HMI is the operator window of the supervisory system.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] It presents plant information to the operating personnel graphically in the form of mimic diagrams, which are a schematic representation of the plant being controlled, and alarm and event logging pages.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The HMI is linked to the SCADA supervisory computer to provide live data to drive the mimic diagrams, alarm displays and trending graphs.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] In many installations the HMI is the graphical user interface for the operator, collects all data from external devices, creates reports, performs alarming, sends notifications, etc.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Mimic diagrams consist of line graphics and schematic symbols to represent process elements, or may consist of digital photographs of the process equipment overlain with animated symbols.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Supervisory operation of the plant is by means of the HMI, with operators issuing commands using mouse pointers, keyboards and touch screens.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] For example, a symbol of a pump can show the operator that the pump is running, and a flow meter symbol can show how much fluid it is pumping through the pipe.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The operator can switch the pump off from the mimic by a mouse click or screen touch.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The HMI will show the flow rate of the fluid in the pipe decrease in real time.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The HMI package for a SCADA system typically includes a drawing program that the operators or system maintenance personnel use to change the way these points are represented in the interface.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] These representations can be as simple as an on-screen traffic light, which represents the state of an actual traffic light in the field, or as complex as a multi-projector display representing the position of all of the elevators in a skyscraper or all of the trains on a railway.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] is a software service within the HMI which accumulates time-stamped data, events, and alarms in a database which can be queried or used to populate graphic trends in the HMI.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The historian is a client that requests data from a data acquisition server.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] An important part of most SCADA implementations is alarm handling.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The system monitors whether certain alarm conditions are satisfied, to determine when an alarm event has occurred.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Once an alarm event has been detected, one or more actions are taken (such as the activation of one or more alarm indicators, and perhaps the generation of email or text messages so that management or remote SCADA operators are informed).
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] In many cases, a SCADA operator may have to acknowledge the alarm event; this may deactivate some alarm indicators, whereas other indicators remain active until the alarm conditions are cleared.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] "Smart" RTUs, or standard PLCs, are capable of autonomously executing simple logic processes without involving the supervisory computer.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Unlike a procedural language like C or FORTRAN, IEC 61131-3 has minimal training requirements by virtue of resembling historic physical control arrays.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] This allows SCADA system engineers to perform both the design and implementation of a program to be executed on an RTU or PLC.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] A programmable automation controller (PAC) is a compact controller that combines the features and capabilities of a PC-based control system with that of a typical PLC.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] PACs are deployed in SCADA systems to provide RTU and PLC functions.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] In many electrical substation SCADA applications, "distributed RTUs" use information processors or station computers to communicate with digital protective relays, PACs, and other devices for I/O, and communicate with the SCADA master in lieu of a traditional RTU.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Since about 1998, virtually all major PLC manufacturers have offered integrated HMI/SCADA systems, many of them using open and non-proprietary communications protocols.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The Remote Terminal Unit (RTU) connects to physical equipment.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Typically, an RTU converts the electrical signals from the equipment to digital values.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] By converting and sending these electrical signals out to equipment the RTU can control equipment.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] SCADA systems have traditionally used combinations of radio and direct wired connections, although SONET/SDH is also frequently used for large systems such as railways and power stations.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The remote management or monitoring function of a SCADA system is often referred to as telemetry.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Some users want SCADA data to travel over their pre-established corporate networks or to share the network with other applications.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The legacy of the early low-bandwidth protocols remains, though.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] SCADA protocols are designed to be very compact.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Many are designed to send information only when the master station polls the RTU.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Typical legacy SCADA protocols include Modbus RTU, RP-570, Profibus and Conitel.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] These communication protocols, with the exception of Modbus (Modbus has been made open by Schneider Electric), are all SCADA-vendor specific but are widely adopted and used.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] These communication protocols are standardized and recognized by all major SCADA vendors.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Many of these protocols now contain extensions to operate over TCP/IP.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Although the use of conventional networking specifications, such as TCP/IP, blurs the line between traditional and industrial networking, they each fulfill fundamentally differing requirements.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Network simulation can be used in conjunction with SCADA simulators to perform various 'what-if' analyses.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] With increasing security demands (such as North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC) and critical infrastructure protection (CIP) in the US), there is increasing use of satellite-based communication.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] This has the key advantages that the infrastructure can be self-contained (not using circuits from the public telephone system), can have built-in encryption, and can be engineered to the availability and reliability required by the SCADA system operator.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Earlier experiences using consumer-grade VSAT were poor.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Modern carrier-class systems provide the quality of service required for SCADA.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] RTUs and other automatic controller devices were developed before the advent of industry wide standards for interoperability.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The result is that developers and their management created a multitude of control protocols.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Among the larger vendors, there was also the incentive to create their own protocol to "lock in" their customer base.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] A list of automation protocols is compiled here.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] An example of efforts by vendor groups to standardize automation protocols is the OPC-UA (formerly "OLE for process control" now Open Platform Communications Unified Architecture).
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Early SCADA system computing was done by large minicomputers.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Common network services did not exist at the time SCADA was developed.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Thus SCADA systems were independent systems with no connectivity to other systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The communication protocols used were strictly proprietary at that time.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The first-generation SCADA system redundancy was achieved using a back-up mainframe system connected to all the remote terminal unit sites and was used in the event of failure of the primary mainframe system.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Some first generation SCADA systems were developed as "turn key" operations that ran on minicomputers such as the PDP-11 series.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] SCADA information and command processing were distributed across multiple stations which were connected through a LAN.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Information was shared in near real time.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Each station was responsible for a particular task, which reduced the cost as compared to first generation SCADA.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The network protocols used were still not standardized.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Since these protocols were proprietary, very few people beyond the developers knew enough to determine how secure a SCADA installation was.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Security of the SCADA installation was usually overlooked.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Similar to a distributed architecture, any complex SCADA can be reduced to the simplest components and connected through communication protocols.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] In the case of a networked design, the system may be spread across more than one LAN network called a process control network (PCN) and separated geographically.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Several distributed architecture SCADAs running in parallel, with a single supervisor and historian, could be considered a network architecture.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] This allows for a more cost-effective solution in very large scale systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The growth of the internet has led SCADA systems to implement web technologies allowing users to view data, exchange information and control processes from anywhere in the world through standard web protocols such as HTTPS and WebSocket for live updates.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The early 2000s saw the proliferation of Web SCADA systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Web SCADA systems use web browsers such as Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox as the graphical user interface (GUI) for the operators HMI.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] This simplifies the client side installation and enables users to access the system from various platforms with web browsers such as servers, personal computers, laptops, tablets and mobile phones.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] SCADA systems that tie together decentralized facilities such as power, oil, gas pipelines, water distribution and wastewater collection systems were designed to be open, robust, and easily operated and repaired, but not necessarily secure.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The move from proprietary technologies to more standardized and open solutions together with the increased number of connections between SCADA systems, office networks and the Internet has made them more vulnerable to types of network attacks that are relatively common in computer security.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Security researcher Jerry Brown submitted a similar advisory regarding a buffer overflow vulnerability in a Wonderware InBatchClient ActiveX control.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Both vendors made updates available prior to public vulnerability release.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Mitigation recommendations were standard patching practices and requiring VPN access for secure connectivity.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Consequently, the security of some SCADA-based systems has come into question as they are seen as potentially vulnerable to cyber attacks.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] SCADA systems are used to control and monitor physical processes, examples of which are transmission of electricity, transportation of gas and oil in pipelines, water distribution, traffic lights, and other systems used as the basis of modern society.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The security of these SCADA systems is important because compromise or destruction of these systems would impact multiple areas of society far removed from the original compromise.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] For example, a blackout caused by a compromised electrical SCADA system would cause financial losses to all the customers that received electricity from that source.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Legacy SCADA deployments can remain difficult to secure because control equipment is often geographically distributed, long-lived, and costly to replace or patch.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] There are many threat vectors to a modern SCADA system.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] One is the threat of unauthorized access to the control software, whether it is human access or changes induced intentionally or accidentally by virus infections and other software threats residing on the control host machine.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Another is the threat of packet access to the network segments hosting SCADA devices.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] In many cases, the control protocol lacks any form of cryptographic security, allowing an attacker to control a SCADA device by sending commands over a network.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] In many cases SCADA users have assumed that having a VPN offered sufficient protection, unaware that security can be trivially bypassed with physical access to SCADA-related network jacks and switches.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Industrial control vendors suggest approaching SCADA security like Information Security with a defense in depth strategy that leverages common IT practices.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Apart from that, research has shown that the architecture of SCADA systems has several other vulnerabilities, including direct tampering with RTUs, communication links from RTUs to the control center, and IT software and databases in the control center.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The RTUs could, for instance, be targets of deception attacks injecting false data or denial-of-service attacks.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The reliable function of SCADA systems in our modern infrastructure may be crucial to public health and safety.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] As such, attacks on these systems may directly or indirectly threaten public health and safety.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Such an attack has already occurred, carried out on Maroochy Shire Council's sewage control system in Queensland, Australia.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Shortly after a contractor installed a SCADA system in January 2000, system components began to function erratically.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Pumps did not run when needed and alarms were not reported.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] More critically, sewage flooded a nearby park and contaminated an open surface-water drainage ditch and flowed 500 meters to a tidal canal.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The SCADA system was directing sewage valves to open when the design protocol should have kept them closed.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Initially this was believed to be a system bug.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Monitoring of the system logs revealed the malfunctions were the result of cyber attacks.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Investigators reported 46 separate instances of malicious outside interference before the culprit was identified.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The attacks were made by a disgruntled ex-employee of the company that had installed the SCADA system.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The ex-employee was hoping to be hired by the utility full-time to maintain the system.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] In April 2008, the *Commission to Assess the Threat to the United States from Electromagnetic Pulse (EMP) Attack* issued a *Critical Infrastructures Report* document which discussed the extreme vulnerability of SCADA systems to an electromagnetic pulse (EMP) event.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] After testing and analysis, the commission concluded: "SCADA systems are vulnerable to EMP insult.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The large numbers and widespread reliance on such systems by all of the Nation’s critical infrastructures represent a systemic threat to their continued operation following an EMP event.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Many vendors of SCADA and control products have begun to address the risks posed by unauthorized access by developing lines of specialized industrial firewall and VPN solutions for TCP/IP-based SCADA networks as well as external SCADA monitoring and recording equipment.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The International Society of Automation (ISA) started formalizing SCADA security requirements in 2007 with a working group, WG4.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] WG4 "deals specifically with unique technical requirements, measurements, and other features required to evaluate and assure security resilience and performance of industrial automation and control systems devices".
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The increased interest in SCADA vulnerabilities has resulted in vulnerability researchers discovering vulnerabilities in commercial SCADA software and more general offensive SCADA techniques presented to the general security community.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] In June 2010, anti-virus security company VirusBlokAda reported the first detection of malware that attacks SCADA systems (Siemens' WinCC/PCS 7 systems) running on Windows operating systems.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The malware is called Stuxnet and uses four zero-day attacks to install a rootkit which in turn logs into the SCADA's database and steals design and control files.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The malware is also capable of changing the control system and hiding those changes.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] The malware was found on 14 systems, the majority of which were located in Iran.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] In October 2013 *National Geographic* released a docudrama titled *American Blackout* which dealt with an imagined large-scale cyber attack on SCADA and the United States' electrical grid.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] Both large and small systems can be built using the SCADA concept.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] These systems can range from just tens to thousands of control loops, depending on the application.
[src:oil-gas-scada/scada] However, SCADA systems may have security vulnerabilities, so the systems should be evaluated to identify risks and solutions implemented to mitigate those risks.
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] A **wellhead** is the component at the surface of an oil or gas well that provides the structural and pressure-containing interface for the drilling and production equipment.
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] The primary purpose of a wellhead is to provide the suspension point and pressure seals for the casing strings that run from the bottom of the hole sections to the surface pressure control equipment.
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] While drilling the oil well, surface pressure control is provided by a blowout preventer (BOP).
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] If the pressure is not contained during drilling operations by the column of drilling fluid, casings, wellhead, and BOP, a well blowout could occur.
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] When the well has been drilled, it is completed to provide an interface with the reservoir rock and a tubular conduit for the well fluids.
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] The surface pressure control is provided by a Christmas tree, which is installed on top of the wellhead, with isolation valves and choke equipment to control the flow of well fluids during production.
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] Wellheads are typically welded onto the first string of casing, which has been cemented in place during drilling operations, to form an integral structure of the well.
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] In exploration wells that are later abandoned, the wellhead may be recovered for refurbishment and re-use.
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] Offshore, where a wellhead is located on the production platform it is called a *surface wellhead*, and if located beneath the water then it is referred to as a subsea wellhead or mudline wellhead.
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] Provides a means of tubing suspension (Tubing is removable pipe installed in the well through which well fluids pass).
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] Provides a means of pressure sealing and isolation between casing at surface when many casing strings are used.
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] Provides pressure monitoring and pumping access to annuli between the different casing/tubing strings.
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] Provides a means of attaching a blowout preventer during drilling.
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] Provides a means of attaching a Christmas tree for production operations.
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] Provides a reliable means of well access.
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] In general well heads are five nominal ratings of wellheads: 2, 3, 5, 10 and 15 (×1000) psi working pressure.
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] They have an operating temperature range of −50 to +250 degrees Fahrenheit.
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] They are used in conjunction with ring type seal gaskets.
[src:oil-gas-scada/wellhead] In general the yield strength of the materials range from 36000 to 75000 psi.
